  "eprint": {
    "title": "Optimal and Error-Free Multi-Valued Byzantine Consensus Through Parallel Execution",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Andrew Loveless",
        "email": "loveless@umich",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Ronald Dreslinski",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Baris Kasikci",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Multi-valued Byzantine Consensus (BC), in which $n$ processes must reach agreement on a single $L$-bit value, is an essential primitive in the design of distributed cryptographic protocols and fault-tolerant distributed systems.\nOne of the most desirable traits for a multi-valued BC protocol is to be error-free.\nIn other words, have zero probability of producing incorrect results.\n\nThe most efficient error-free multi-valued BC protocols are built as extension protocols, which reduce agreement on large values to agreement on small sequences of bits whose lengths are independent of $L$.\nThe best extension protocols achieve $\\mathcal{O}(Ln)$ communication complexity, which is optimal, when $L$ is large relative to $n$.\nUnfortunately, all known error-free and communication-optimal BC extension protocols require each process to broadcast at least $n$ bits with a binary Byzantine Broadcast (BB) protocol.\nThis design limits the scalability of these protocols to many processes, since when $n$ is large, the binary broadcasts significantly inflate the overall number of bits communicated by the extension protocol.\n\nIn this paper, we present Byzantine Consensus with Parallel Execution (BCPE), the first error-free and communication-optimal BC extension protocol in which each process only broadcasts a single bit with a binary BB protocol.\nBCPE is a synchronous and deterministic protocol, and tolerates $f < n/3$ faulty processes (the best resilience possible).\nOur evaluation shows that BCPE's design makes it significantly more scalable than the best existing protocol by Ganesh and Patra.\nFor 1,000 processes to agree on 2 MB of data, BCPE communicates $10.92\\times$ fewer bits.\nFor agreement on 10 MB of data, BCPE communicates $6.97\\times$ fewer bits.\nBCPE also matches the best existing protocol in all other standard efficiency metrics.",
    "keywords": [
      "Byzantine Agreement",
      "Byzantine Consensus",
      "Extension Protocols",
      "Round Complexity",
      "Communication Complexity"
    ],
